Dear Abinandan,

Thank you for this evaluation. Before addressing the technical findings, 
let me first acknowledge what this mail represents. The PR print PDF you 
have attached — PR No. 368 for Ashok Textile Mills, Spinning Division — 
is the first actual SPINRISE output document produced from the ASP.NET 
Core backend. The company header, Kalsofte logo, PR details, three line 
items with machine numbers, previous purchase rate columns, approximate 
cost, and the three-signature footer are all correctly populated. 
Whatever its POC status, this is a working transaction print from a 
migrated VB6 screen running on a web platform. *That is a meaningful 
milestone for this project.*

*Now on the technical findings.
*
*On the FastReports evaluation*

*Your core finding is correct and confirmed:* there is no reliable 
automated .rpt to .frx conversion. The .rpt → XML → .frx path is the 
right approach, and manual redesign per report is the realistic 
expectation. This is not a failure of the tool — Crystal Reports and 
FastReports use fundamentally different rendering models, and 
pixel-perfect automated conversion has never been reliably achieved 
between them. The effort cost is in the manual redesign and fine-tuning 
per report, not in a tool limitation that can be procured around.

The Free tier is not viable for SPINRISE production. No XLSX export, no 
CSV, and limited PDF capabilities are not minor gaps in an ERP system 
that delivers GST-compliant invoices, download reports, and MIS to 50+ 
customer sites. *This was always going to be a paid tool decision and 
your analysis confirms the reasons clearly.
*
*Decision: FastReports Standard tier*

Let's consider to Procure the Standard tier at approximately $499 per 
developer per year. This covers the desktop designer, standard exports, 
and full PDF capability for all Phase 1 transaction print requirements — 
PR, PO, RMI, Sales Order, Salary. The Enterprise tier ($799) adds the 
online report designer and report server, which are Phase 2+ features 
for customer self-service report customisation. We do not need 
Enterprise for Phase 1. We will arrange the Standard tier licence as and 
when required.

*One immediate action alongside procurement:* run a 1 to 2 day POC on 
the Crystal Reports import plugin that comes with the paid version. Use 
a complex report as the test subject — the PO print (Cry_RMIPO_JAT_NEW) 
or the Sales Order print (RepLSales.rpt) would be good candidates 
because both have multi-section layouts, grouped line items, and 
conditional visibility. If the import plugin recovers 40 to 50 percent 
of the layout correctly, it meaningfully reduces manual rework across 
the 50-plus Crystal reports in Phases 1 and 2. If it recovers less, you 
have confirmed the manual path and we plan the effort accordingly. This 
POC should run in parallel with Phase 1 development work, not ahead of it.

*Decision: EPPlus for Excel export, confirmed
*
Your suggestion to use EPPlus for Excel and CSV export is the correct 
architectural decision and I am confirming it as the SPINRISE standard. 
The separation is clean: FastReports handles all print-layout PDF 
documents (transaction prints, registers, format reports), and EPPlus 
handles all data-export Excel documents (MIS downloads, attendance 
registers, payroll abstracts, stock reports). EPPlus gives programmatic 
cell-level control, which produces more reliable and structured output 
than a layout-based export engine for tabular data. This is how we will 
build it across all modules.

*One item on the PR print to investigate*

Looking at the attached print, Item 1 (Item Code 560R002) shows the 
description beginning with '(IN ACTIVE) ROTO INJECT OIL...'. The PR form 
FSD documents that the item lookup must filter IsItemActive = 1, meaning 
inactive items should not appear on a PR. The presence of an inactive 
item in this test print could mean one of two things: either the test 
data includes an inactive item that was entered before the active-filter 
was implemented, or the IsItemActive filter is not yet applied in the 
trial conversion. Please confirm which it is and ensure the production 
implementation applies the active-item filter on item selection.

*One question before we finalise FastReports as the standard
*
The original SPINRISE blueprint included RDLC (Microsoft Report 
Definition Language) as an alternative to Crystal Reports. It is free, 
ships with Visual Studio, and integrates natively with ASP.NET Core. 
Your analysis compares Crystal to FastReports but does not include RDLC. 
I am not asking you to reverse the recommendation — your POC work points 
clearly toward FastReports. But*I would like a brief note from you on 
why FastReports is the better choice over RDLC for SPINRISE.* The two 
main points I expect are: RDLC requires SQL Server Reporting Services 
for server-side rendering (an infrastructure dependency we want to 
avoid), and RDLC has significant limitations in complex multi-section 
layouts and conditional banding that our transaction prints require. If 
those are your conclusions, confirm them and I will formally close RDLC 
as a considered and rejected option in the SPINRISE architecture log.

*Two things I need from you to complete this decision*

*First:* how many Crystal Reports are in scope for Phase 1 modules (M01 
PO, M02 RMI, M03 Domestic Sales, M04 HR and Payroll)? A rough count from 
the module FSD documents will do. Or you could find out from the 
respective modules IST member. This gives us the migration workload 
estimate.

*Second: *once the paid licence is in place, share your POC findings on 
the import plugin within one week. Specifically: what percentage of 
layout recovery, how many hours of manual correction were needed, and 
your recommendation on whether to use the plugin as a starting point or 
start from a blank FastReports template for each report.

*Overall*

You have moved from theory to working output in a short time. The PR 
print is evidence that the SPINRISE stack is capable of producing the 
transaction documents our customers expect. The reporting architecture 
decision is now clear:*FastReports Standard for PDFs, EPPlus for Excel, 
import plugin to be validated. Proceed on that basis.
*
Regards,
T. Mani

